Here's how to handle draft persistence with .NET MAUI's lifecycle events:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "NoteDraft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated += OnAppResumed;
    }

    private void OnAppBackgrounded(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Save draft to Preferences (lightweight key-value store)
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Restore only if the editor is empty (avoid overwriting active edits)
        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(NoteEditor.Text))
        {
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
        }
    }

    // Clean up when navigating away
    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated -= OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated -= OnAppResumed;
    }

    // Clear draft after an intentional save
    private void OnSaveClicked(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // ... your save logic ...
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concept | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| `Window.Deactivated` | Fires when app loses focus (backgrounded) |
| `Window.Activated` | Fires when app regains focus |
| `Preferences` | Fast key-value store, ideal for small text drafts |
| Cleanup | Unsubscribe in `OnDisappearing` to avoid leaks |

**For larger drafts** (e.g., rich text or multi-field forms), use `SecureStorage` or write to a temp file via `FileSystem.CacheDirectory` instead of `Preferences`, which is best for strings under ~1 KB.
